// Q1: Cialdini's Seventh Principle (MC, Remembering)
::Q1 Cialdini Seventh Principle::Which principle did Cialdini add as the seventh principle in the 2021 expanded edition of "Influence"?{
=Unity#Unity was added by Cialdini in 2021 as the seventh principle, focusing on shared group identity and belonging through "we" language and common values.
~Consistency#Consistency is part of "Commitment and Consistency," one of the original six principles, not the seventh one added later.
~Urgency#Urgency is not a separate Cialdini principle, though it relates to the Scarcity principle (limited time/quantity).
~Transparency#Transparency is an ethical standard for using persuasion principles, not one of Cialdini's seven principles itself.
}

// Q2: SUCCESs Framework Acronym (MC, Remembering)
::Q2 SUCCESs Second C::What does the second "C" in the SUCCESs framework stand for?{
=Credible#The second "C" stands for Credible, which means building trust through sources, vivid details, or testable claims.
~Concrete#Concrete is the FIRST "C" in SUCCESs (vivid, tangible details), not the second.
~Consistent#Consistency is not part of the SUCCESs framework; the letters are Simple, Unexpected, Concrete, Credible, Emotional, Stories.
~Clear#Clear is not part of the SUCCESs framework, though "Simple" (the "S") involves clarity.
}

// Q3: Aristotle's Three Appeals (MC, Remembering)
::Q3 Ethos Credibility::Which of Aristotle's three rhetorical appeals focuses on establishing the speaker's credibility and character?{
=Ethos#Ethos establishes the speaker's credibility through expertise, common ground, character, and appropriate balance.
~Pathos#Pathos appeals to the audience's emotions, values, and beliefs—not the speaker's credibility.
~Logos#Logos uses logic, data, and structured reasoning to support arguments—it focuses on evidence, not credibility.
~Kairos#Kairos refers to timing and context; it's not one of Aristotle's three rhetorical appeals covered in this lecture.
}

